[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This camera is so much fun to capture Gaussian splatting with mainly because you can pick in so much information in the same amount [music] of time especially compared to a normal 2D camera. However, there\'s always been something I wish this camera could do and that is to have the ability to fly. Earlier this year I saw the unveiling of'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the Insta360 A1 which is literally just that an actual 360 camera on a drone. And so I\'ve been fortunate enough over the last few weeks to be testing out the A1 to see how well can this device capture Gaussian splatting. So in this'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video we\'re going to take a look at this drone, what it can do and most importantly how well can it reconstruct Gaussian splatting. But first let\'s talk about what Gaussian splatting even is. Gaussian splatting is one way to represent a radiance field. You can kind'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of think about it like a 3D photograph where you can view it from any angle. Because of this having access to 360 data is incredibly important because it allows us to capture so much more about the world around us in the same amount of time. This video is sponsored by'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Insta360 but all of my opinions contained in this video are my own. They don\'t have any influence over it and I will give my honest opinions about this drone. So I am not historically a big drone person. I have very little experience flying and to be honest when'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the drone arrived I started to think to myself like okay I actually feel a bit off the deep end in terms of my familiarity and being able to really feel confident flying it. That said that anxiety lasted pretty much up until I put on the actual goggles and then I had'

[01:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a complete realization. I realized it\'s so similar to actually virtual reality headsets I\'ve used in the past where basically you were just pointing where you would like to go. This made me feel so much more comfortable much more quickly than I expected to. And once I'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'got over that initial hurdle then like oh man I don\'t know if I could do this it became so much fun to fly around where I genuinely was not expecting to like this drone as much as I do. It\'s so much fun to fly. So while you\'re flying'

[01:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you get this wrapped around perspective that really allows you to see everywhere that you\'re going and it makes the flying experience so much more intuitive than I actually expected and I was very pleasantly surprised by that. So let\'s actually talk about how you use the'

[01:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'drone and you control it with this remote. And at first I actually was feeling a bit overwhelmed when I looked at it cuz I was like okay I don\'t really know what to do with this. How am I going to fly this? It actually changed pretty quickly for me. The first'

[02:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[snorts] thing that you do is you go through tutorial and normally I am not the biggest fan of tutorials I typically skip them or skip through them but in this case I actually decided that I would really pay attention and it did actually make me feel significantly more comfortable flying the drone because as'

[02:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I said I don\'t have a ton of experience actually using drones. So when you go to actually turn on the remote you\'re going to double press the power button right here like so. It\'s going to power on it\'s going to make that noise and it actually turns on'

[02:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'super quickly too which is very nice. And once you have it here you then are going to pair it to your goggles which for me once you do it the first time it\'s just an automatic thing. So once you\'re ready to fly we\'re actually going to take the remote we\'re going to push up on this white button twice like that'

[02:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s going to start the motor and then when you\'re ready to actually take off you\'re going to actually just hold it up and it\'s going to take about 3 seconds or so and then it will the drone will take off and lift up about maybe 5 or so feet off the ground. And the way that you fly is actually very intuitive and I'

[02:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'think the reason why I felt intimidated at first was because when I saw other videos of the A1 you\'d only really see it from the cockpit view. But basically the way it works with the remote is that you have this little trigger at the back here and as you depress it further in it'

[03:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'makes the drone fly faster and vice versa. But it\'s very quite easy to fly. It\'s a bit more intuitive where once you press the trigger you\'re just going to simply point in the direction that you want it to fly and you\'ll see it reflected in the actual goggles. If'

[03:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'ve ever used other virtual reality headset like say a Meta Quest it\'s going to be very similar where you\'ll see the actual beam extend out into the field of view and you\'re just going to simply going to point it where is you\'d like it to go. And for me that was a big tipping'

[03:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'point where I was like oh I actually can do this. This is actually not so bad at all. There are three distinct modes that you can fly with the A1. There is the sport mode there is the normal mode and then there is the cinematic mode. And for me every single flight I have done I'

[03:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'put it on to cinematic mode because when we take a look at what Gaussian splatting loves it really loves sharp frames and it loves a lot of parallax. And so for me there\'s really not a need to fly overly quickly. And despite the'

[03:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'max flight speed of kept about I think 6 miles an hour on cinematic mode I\'m still able to capture so much during that time because remember we\'re capturing 360 data and that is just radically dropping down the capture'

[04:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'time. Because of this I don\'t need to be nearly as stressed out as I thought I would be about the battery life because when I was first looking at the specs I was saying okay I have like roughly 24 minutes of flight time but in practice what actually happened was that I would'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fly for like roughly 10 minutes or so and then realize that I already had everything that I need because remember we\'re capturing from every single angle. And so for me it became such a pleasant experience to actually not have to stress about the flight time because I'

[04:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'already knew that I was capturing everything that I would need. And so now it\'s hard for me to envision why drones wouldn\'t natively be just 360 in the future because at least for Gaussian splatting we\'re able to capture so much more information about the world around'

[04:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'us. And from using this drone I\'ve just like it\'s hard for me to realize why we would ever go back. This just makes so much more sense specifically if you\'re trying to reconstruct the world around you. You might also be curious to know do I need another SD card while I\'m'

[04:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'flying? And the A1 does come with 20 gigabytes of on device storage and for me the first couple of days I actually didn\'t have a separate SD card but so what I would basically do was I would fly for roughly 10 minutes or so I would then just stop flying I\'d go hook it up'

[05:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to my computer transfer over the data wipe it and then keep on flying. So technically you potentially could get away with just doing that but I would say definitely adding an extra SD card would make your life a little bit less'

[05:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stressful. I found that shooting at 8K 30 frames a second would result in about 10 gigabytes for every 8 minutes of flight time. The A1 is also 249 grams meaning you\'re under the 250 gram limit to register with the FAA.'

[05:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That said if you do use the high capacity battery then you would need to register with the FAA in order to legally fly. That\'s enough information about the drone itself and the flying experience. Let\'s get into the thing that people probably care about the most'

[05:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is how well do the files reconstruct? And for me I would say I\'ve been super impressed by the fidelity of reconstructions that I\'ve gotten from this. Now I\'m talking like super low floaters. Like there\'s almost'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'non-existent amount of floaters in my reconstructions which is really nice to have uh as you\'re going out to shoot just to feel that confident that what I\'m shooting is going to reconstruct really well. Once you get back home and'

[06:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'start to transfer over data to your computer Insta360 does have Insta360 Studio which is where all of our exporting is going to occur in the beginning of our post-processing. So now we\'re going to go and download the Insta360 Studio which is pretty much the'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'same thing as Insta360 Studio. So we\'re going to go through the install wizard it\'s going to take maybe like a minute or so and now once we\'re done we\'re just going to hit finish. It\'s going to actually open up Insta360 Studio and it\'s going to import the captures that we have so far which are all INSV files'

[06:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is the native file type for Insta360 as well as Insta360 too. And we\'re going to load them all and we can see here the 360 view and if we zoom in actually it start to undistort it and we can start to see how it was actually captured but we\'re going to go straight'

[06:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to export here. We\'re going to hit 360 video. Super important we\'re going to max out the bit rate always when we go to export this and we just need to actually set our file path to about where it\'s going to save so I just changed the folder and now it is'

[06:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exporting. We can actually follow along with the export time depending on this length of your video and the strength of your computer it will take more or less time. I think for me it takes about like 10-15 minutes or so and once it is complete then we are going to move on to'

[07:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the next part of the actual reconstruction process. So we\'re going to use a plugin from someone named Kodo Hiby. It is a paid plugin though he does allow you to actually build from source for free but I figured it\'s like $15 or so I decided just to purchase it. I load'

[07:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the directory of where the video is and what\'s very nice about this is that it will actually generate our image masks for us so if there\'s things like a person or a dog or something like this we can actually go ahead and automate that for ourselves which is really nice.'

[07:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And so right here I\'m just going to be creating a folder that essentially is going to be where the actual video is exported to where it\'s actually going to save all of the individual still frames. So we\'re going to be converting our'

[07:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video into still images here and this also takes about 10-15 minutes to run depending on the size of the video and your computer but it is going to just slice up very sharp frames for us and also do our masks and and something that'

[07:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is super super nice. I very much like this plugin. So now it is done we\'re going to get our completion message and and we\'re going to take a look at the frames really quick so we\'re going to see how much information is shown here. You know we\'re really being able to'

[08:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'capture a lot of information but you can see that I was in the right there of that image and we can go to our masks now we can click on it and see that that little like black area is now being successfully masked out which is really nice. And so now we\'re ready to start'

[08:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the next part which is going to be an Agisoft Metashape which is another paid software but it is super fast structure for motion so it\'s what we\'re going to go with. So we\'re going to first load in our images and select the folder. And now that our images are in there too'

[08:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what we\'re going to do is we\'re actually going to going to go to the camera calibration we\'re going to actually update it from frame over to spherical because that is the type of image that we are working with at this point and we\'re just going to hit okay. And now we are going to start to actually bring in'

[08:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the image masks that were created so go to import masks and we\'re going to import the actual file name language here to just be file name.png. Hit okay. And then we\'re going to point it to where our masks are actually located and it\'s going to load them in. It\'s going'

[09:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to take a couple seconds and now we have both our images and we have our masks. So we can go ahead and we can hit align images and just like before this process will take quite a bit of time especially depending on the computer that you\'re'

[09:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'working with. For me I think that this took me a little bit over an hour to process all of this. And so we can follow it along as it actually goes and aligns everything. And basically what it\'s doing right now is it\'s aligning everything in a three-dimensional space. It\'s basically asking itself where is'

[09:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'each camera looking in a given 3D space. And so now it\'s done we can see the result of that with the two towers coming from the return to home function but we can see it has a really solid idea as to where each individual frame was taken. And so now what we can start'

[09:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to do is we can begin to actually clean it up just a little bit by cleaning up the tie points based upon the reprojection error and we\'re going to clean up maybe like the top like 0.5% of matches in the actual alignment so we\'ll hit okay. And then we\'re just going to'

[09:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have to optimize the cameras. And now once that has been complete then we can actually start to move into exporting into COLMAP, which is how platforms like Polycam and Luma AI Studio and Brush, they all accept COLMAP format. So, first'

[10:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re going to export the cameras, and even though it says COLMAP here, we\'re going to go to Agisoft.xml, and we\'re going to type in cameras. Once we have that saved, then we can go and export the next thing, which is export the point cloud, and I\'m just going to call'

[10:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it sparse just to be a bit consistent with everything, and I\'m going to hit save. Now that both of these have been saved, we\'re going to go to the next part of the COLMAP to Agisoft plugin, which is the Agisoft 360° to COLMAP converter. So, we\'re going to link where all the'

[10:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'original frames are, and I actually make a mistake right here, where we actually need to link the XML to the actual corresponding file. I put it in the wrong folder here, so I actually had to redo it, but then we go and link the PLY file correctly, and then we also just need to create an output folder as to'

[10:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'where we actually want this output to go. And this one I\'m going to call final because this is actually going to be the folder that we drop in everything into Polycam or Luma AI. This is where the actual final step takes place. Again, we'

[10:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'do have the capability of running YOLO, which is going to do all our auto masking for us, and I\'m just going to leave it as it is. Zero is humans, I think 16 is dogs. There\'s no dogs, but I\'m just going to leave it like this anyways. This is also going to take a'

[11:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'little bit of time to this step. I think it takes about maybe half an hour for me to run everything, but once it is complete, we will finally be ready to put it into some of the reconstruction platforms themselves. And so now, it is'

[11:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'done, so what I\'m going to do is I\'m going to go ahead and I\'m going to open Luma AI Studio. Now that it is open, I\'m going to go to file and hit import data set, and I\'m going to select that final folder. We can see here we have our'

[11:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'images, we have our sparse, and we also have our masks all loaded in correctly. So, we hit load, and then after a couple seconds, it\'s going to see all the frustums, and we can see it has been loaded in correctly. And for Luma AI Studio, there is one really important'

[11:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'note, and that\'s actually the mask mode is we need to set it to ignore. We\'re just going to update the number of total Gaussians that it\'s going to reconstruct. A couple other settings I like to change is adding on the MIP filter as well as PPISP. And then from there, we are actually ready to hit'

[11:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'training. It does take a little bit more time to actually go ahead and reconstruct everything, but at this point, we are finally reconstructing. And if you\'re wondering how to bring it into something like Polycam, we\'re going to open Polycam here, we\'re going to bring that same final folder into it.'

[12:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then we\'re going to select the images folder as well as the cameras, the images, and the points 3D file, and we\'re going to drag and drop it directly onto the screen. We\'re going to expand where it says image masks, and we\'re going to go back to the file menu, and we\'re going to take the mask folder, and'

[12:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re just going to simply drag and drop into that window there, and we\'re going to set remove background. And finally, we\'re going to select photometric compensation, which is the same thing as PPISP. We\'re going to increase the total splat count, and then we\'re also going to hit create sky model. And from there,'

[12:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it begins the actual training process, too. Now that we\'ve finally trained everything, let\'s take a look at some of the results. And as we can see, the fidelity is looking super super awesome on all of them. We are getting what looks like almost the same as the actual'

[12:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'input video, but again, these are actual complete 3D reconstructions, meaning we can go anywhere that we would like to go in these scenes. We could even go underwater in this pond example, for instance, and take a look at what\'s underneath the water. We can see that'

[12:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the reflections aren\'t necessarily exactly true, but we get this really crazy mirror world, where we can see a bunch of upside down trees. I really love exploring the scenes like this and kind of like breaking that fourth wall. If you\'d rather just go the cloud-based'

[13:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'route, there is a platform called Splat AI, which it makes it very easy to simply just drag and drop directly onto the window, and it does actually accept the INSP directly, meaning you don\'t need to actually export out the stitched MP4 before you upload. So, you can'

[13:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really just drag and drop and just wait for it to upload to the platform. And then about a couple hours later, once it finishes processing, you can just start going to check out your reconstructions. And we can see the results are actually looking pretty solid, too, from Splat'

[13:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'AI, which is also very nice. Though, I will say that Splat AI is a paid service, too, so just keep that in mind. While you can just drag and drop and get a lot more easy functionality, you do have to pay. One additional platform'

[13:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that also has 360 cloud support is Niantic Scaniverse, and I misread the documentation and thought you could train directly on the INSPs, but for the A1, they actually only support the stitched MP4s, so I accidentally burnt'

[13:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all my credits trying to process the INSP, so I will have to go back and revisit that at some point in the future. I would love to eventually see a native Gaussian splatting platform from Insta360, but I do think it probably will be a bit'

[14:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of time before we have that capability. In case you are curious to check out the actual reconstructions for yourself, I have uploaded all of them onto SuperSplat, and I\'ve included the links to them in the description below. So, with all of this in mind, would I use'

[14:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this drone regularly? And honestly, the answer is a resounding yes. This drone has been so much fun to actually fly with, and for a couple reasons. One, it is super light. Two, I\'m able to capture so much more information about the world'

[14:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'around me in the same amount of time compared to like, say, a traditional drone. And three, the splats that you get from it are awesome. And they\'re really really strong. So, for me, I\'m really looking forward to continuing to travel with this, to get better at using'

[14:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it. And this has been like the first time where I\'ve actually really felt compelled to go and bring a drone with me. So, for me, I am stoked about this drone. And as a reminder, this video is sponsored by Insta360, but all of my opinions in this video are my own. And when the drone'

[15:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'first arrived, I really wasn\'t sure what to expect from it. I really felt like it was a little bit, um, out of my league, but that said, I have become significantly more fond of this drone, and it will definitely be coming with me'

[15:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wherever I go. And to that end, I was able to convince the Insta360 team to offer a discount to subscribers of this channel. So, if you\'re interested in potentially purchasing the drone, there will be a link in the description for you to go ahead and do that at a discount. In terms of what\'s next, I\'m'

[15:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'planning to take footage from the A1 and then pair it with a capture from the X5, and we\'ll see how we can reconstruct super lifelike 3D on across a very large area. I imagine that this would work really well. I haven\'t had a chance to'

[15:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'try it just yet, but it is at the very top of my list. So, if you\'re interested in that, please consider following along. And if you\'ve been thinking about this drone for more industrial applications, I really do think that it would do an amazing job in places where you really need to be doing some kind of'

[15:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reality capture. So, places like construction or geospatial, this is probably going to be a very capable device for you to actually capture and document your work. But what do you guys think of this drone? I\'m not sure there is a better Gaussian splatting drone in'

[16:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the US, but I am sure that 360 drones are definitely a better option to capture Gaussian splattings. You\'re just getting so much more information in the same amount of time, and I\'m really excited to keep flying and capturing with it. If you\'re new to this channel,'

[16:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or if you found something interesting in today\'s video, please consider subscribing, and with that, I will see you all in the next one.'
